@node "introduction" "Introduction"


   What is Amitory?




   Amitory is a chat program made for use on a local
   area network (usually ethernet with tcp/ip packets)
   It does not need any servers because all messages
   are sent by UDP to the broadcast address
   It's probably the best chat program for use
   internally on a LAN!


   It's designed for a maximum of 254 users, and it's
   required that all users that are going to chat with
   each other have the same three parts of there IP
   addresses. Netmask should (but not nescessarily (?))
   be 255.255.255.0 (check your tcp/ip stack).



   Background




   Oratory for PC have existed in some years already,
   but no Amiga version have been made.
   I waited a year for a Linux version to port, but
   the linux port of Amitory didn't progress to fast,
   and was quite buggy.

   Because of this, I decided to make an Amiga
   version of this program, without building it on any
   code of the pc or linux versions.

   I didn't have much experience with coding, but I'd
   made some small tools in arexx earlier.
   That is why I decided to use arexx.

   At first my plan was as simple as just see what
   the other sayd, without any possibility to join or
   to send messages. But after some coding, I found
   out how to expand it. After some days of coding,
   I had a complete Oratory for the Amiga in mind,
   and I called it Amitory.

   I needed a GUI too, and because I do like MUI,
   the choice was simple -MuiRexx to make the GUI



   PS: The Win95/98 version uses 4 Mb of memory, and
       are 1Mb of size! :)
@endnode

@node "Needed" "Needed"

   Needed files and equipment



   Computer
      An Amiga computer
      Amiga OS 3.0 (2.04+ systems may work, but is not tested)
      Required: 68020 CPU - Recommended: 68040 CPU
      Harddisk required
      Connection to a local area network (Usually ethernet)
      TCP/IP stack with UDP support (Amitcp/Genesis/Miami)


   Programs
      Mui (Aminet: util/libs/mui38usr.lha)
      Muirexx V3 (Aminet: dev/mui/MuiRexx_3_0a.lha)
      Rexxmast running (Usually started automaticly at bootup)
      c:Flashfind (included)
      c:copy, c:makedir, c:delete, c:run, c:assign, c:rx (system)


   Libraries
      reqtools.library (Included)
      rexxreqtools.library (Included)
      rexxtricks.library (Included)
      rexxsupport.library (Included in system)
      rmh.library (Included)
      rxsocket.library (Included)


   Included programs/Libs is in the Files_For_Install directory.
   This must be installed first.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"


   Installation



   Installation is really simple
   Just copy the whole Amitorydir anywhere you like

   Then make sure that all @{"required files" link "Needed" 0} are installed

   Included programs/Libs is in the Files_For_Install directory.
   This must be installed first.

   Then run the prefs program Amitory_Prefs
   BEFORE starting Amitory
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"


   How to use




   Make sure that all @{"required files" link "Needed" 0} are installed.

   If it's the first time you are running it
   or have reinstalled, changed IP or something,
   then run the preferences program Amitory_Prefs
   first.

   Then start Amitory

   After a short time, a window will appear
   (hopefully) with a welcome message. Soon the
   message '<nick> joins' will appear, where <nick>
   is your nick, and your nick will appear in the
   user list at the right.

   Now you are in. After a minute or so, the other
   users online have appeared in the user list.



   To send a public message, then just write the
   message on the bottom string gadget, and push
   <enter>.

   To send a private message, write /<nick>: first
   in the message, where <nick> is the nick of the
   person you are trying to send a private message
   to (It may also be the last number of the IP
   address (also appeared in the user list))

   To change the topic, type it at the top string
   gadget, and push <enter>

   Other options are also available, used in the
   same way as IRC commands. Type /help or /cmdlist
   to get a list of all available commands.
   (all commands must be typed in lower case)

   nick: To change your nick
   status: to change the status of what you're doing
   name: To change your name
   current: to change your current state. But it's
      much easier to change it be using the
      cycle gadget at the bottom right.
   me: To send a message as emote.
      ex: "/me is eating" gives the result
      "<nick> is eating" where <nick> is your nick.
   topic: To change the topic
   beep: To send a beep to someone
   hardbeep: A harder beep than beep. should not
      be used too much...
   refresh: Update the information of an other
      online user (should not be nescessary)
   help, cmdlist, info: help message
        whois: Get userinformation about someone



   Symbols on the user list:

   Green square:   Here
   Yello square:   Away from keyboard
   red square:     Away
   Question mark:  Idle
   zzz:            Sleeping
   No access sign: Do not disturb
   Hot dog:        Eating
   TV:             Watching TV
   Phone:          On the phone
@endnode

